By a 13-0 vote (Cuba and Yemen abstaining), the UN approved trade and military  sanctions against Iraq, including a ban on oil purchases, as punishment for invading  Kuwait.
Iraq reacted by rounding up Britons, Americans and West Germans in Kuwait,  taking some to Iraq.
Saddam Hussein ordered evacuation drills in Baghdad in case of US  or Israeli attacks.
Many Kuwaitis fled to Saudi Arabia.
Oil prices soared to a four-year  high.
One reason for invading Kuwait was Kuwaiti reluctance to slow its oil flow to  create higher prices, which Iraq was pressing for to rebuild its war-damaged economy  and settle $80 billion in foreign debts. 
